addition.102: * Returns {@code table[index]}, where {@code table} is actually a {@code byte[]}, {@code
addition.103: * short[]}, or {@code int[]}. When it is a {@code byte[]} or {@code short[]}, the returned value
addition.104: * is unsigned, so the range of possible returned values is 0–255 or 0–65535, respectively.
addition.117: * Sets {@code table[index]} to {@code entry}, where {@code table} is actually a {@code byte[]},
addition.118: * {@code short[]}, or {@code int[]}. The value of {@code entry} should fit in the size of the
addition.119: * assigned array element, when seen as an unsigned value. So if {@code table} is a {@code byte[]}
addition.120: * then we should have {@code 0 ≤ entry ≤ 255}, and if {@code table} is a {@code short[]} then we
addition.121: * should have {@code 0 ≤ entry ≤ 65535}. It is the caller's responsibility to ensure this.
